TY  - JOUR
AB  - A good is often more valuable to any user, the more others use compatible goods. We show that this effect may inhibit innovation. If an installed base exists and transition to a new standard must be gradual, early adopters bear a disproportionate share of transient incompatibility costs. This can cause "excess inertia." The installed base, however, is "stranded" if the new standard is adopted: this may create "excess momentum." These dynamic effects have strategic implications.
AU  - Farrell, Joseph
AU  - Saloner, Garth
